ge test callbacks | **Warn** | Low severity, `agent_risk: 0.34-0.35`. Not blocking alone, but they make targeted test edits harder. Split when modifying those suites. |\\n| `crime_00043`-`crime_00051` weak assertion matchers | **Warn** | Low severity, `agent_risk: 0.34`. These have some assertions, unlike the zero-assertion tests, so I would not block; improve when touching those tests. |\\n\\n**Ignore**\\n\\n| Finding | Decision | Why |\\n|---|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00004` duplicate `myParseInt` in examples | **Ignore** | Medium severity, `agent_risk: 0.62`, but both occurrences are examples. Duplication may be clearer for standalone docs/examples than extracting a shared helper. |\\n| `crime_00025` large anonymous test wrapper | **Ignore** | Medium severity, `agent_risk: 0.45`. A single 125-line test callback is not ideal, but not enough to block or warn unless the suite is actively flaky or unclear. |\\n| `crime_00026` scattered `\\\"PORT\\\"` literal | **Ignore** | Medium severity, `agent_risk: 0.60`. In CLI examples and typings, `PORT` is likely intentional domain vocabulary, not duplicated policy. |\\n| `crime_00029`/`crime_00030` boolean naming drift | **Ignore** | Medium severity, `agent_risk: 0.59`. Names like `required`, `optional`, `variadic`, `allowUnknown`, and `displayHelp` are established Commander-style API terms; renaming would likely harm compatibility/readability. |\\n| `crime_00037` commented-out code in test comment | **Ignore** | Low severity, `agent_risk: 0.36`. Small historical note in a test; clean it later, but not review-significant. |\\n| `crime_00041` boolean naming drift in `lib/option.js` | **Ignore** | Low severity, `agent_risk: 0.49`. Same API-idiom reasoning as above. |\\n| `crime_00052` logic in comments | **Ignore** | Low severity, `agent_risk: 0.31`, confidence only `0.65`. The comment is a reminder about historical signal behavior, not clearly an unencoded rule. |\\n\\nNet: block until the core command file/function shape is reduc