al.\\n\\nRefactor plan: keep public API names if compatibility requires it, but rename internal helpers around side effects. For example: `runBuild`, `runAllBuilds`, `createRollupConfigWithLifecycle`, `cleanOutputOnBuildStart`, or extract pure `createRollupOptions` from impure `prepareRollupBuild`.\\n\\nWhat agents can get wrong today: they may call or move these functions assuming they are cheap and pure, invoke them during dry-run/config inspection, or reorder them before realizing they mutate filesystem/logging state.\\n\\n**option_bag_junk_drawer**\\n\\n- `src/rollup.ts`\\n  - `getRollupConfig(options)` reads at least 10 fields: `cjsInterop`, `clean`, `dts`, `entry`, `external`, `format`, `outDir`, `outExtension`, etc.\\n\\nThe scan also flags this pattern in `src/esbuild/index.ts`, but not in `src/index.ts` or `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`.\\n\\nRefactor plan: introduce narrow named input types at module boundaries. For Rollup, create something like `RollupConfigInput` with only fields owned by Rollup config generation, then destructure at the function boundary. If some fields are normalized earlier, pass a `NormalizedBuildOptions` instead of the raw user options bag.\\n\\nWhat agents can get wrong today: they may add another read from `options` without knowing whether it is raw CLI input, normalized config, or Rollup-only state. That makes it easy to use pre-normalized values, miss defaults, or accidentally couple Rollup to unrelated CLI/build concerns.\\n\\n**return_shape_roulette**\\n\\n- `src/esbuild/svelte.ts`\\n  - `sveltePlugin` returns 6 object-literal shapes.\\n  - `setup` returns 6 object-literal shapes.\\n  - anonymous callback returns 5 object-literal shapes.\\n  - Examples include `{ args, namespace, path }`, `{ location, text }`, and `{ code }`.\\n\\nRefactor plan: add explicit esbuild callback return types and name branch-specific constructors. For example: `toResolveResult`, `toLoadResult`, `toSvelteError`, `toSvelteWarning`. Use esbuild’s `OnResolveResult`, `OnLoadResult`, and diagnostic types where possible, or local aliases if the library types are too broad.\\n\\nWhat agents can get wrong today: they may copy the wrong return shape into the wrong callback, omit required fields like `contents`/`loader`, return diagnostics where esbuild expects load results, or “fix” TypeScript by widening everything instead of preserving the esbuild contract.\\n\\n**supporting risks**\\n\\n- `src/index.ts` has `sync_io_in_hotpath` in `normalizeOptions` from `fs.existsSync`.\\n- `src/rollup.ts` has `direct_date` from `Date.now()` uses.\\n- `src/index.ts` and `src/rollup.ts` are also load-bearing by connectivity, so broad rewrites should be staged.\\n\\nSuggested order:\\n\\n1. Add narrow internal types first: normalized build options, Rollup config input, Svelte plugin result helpers.\\n2. Extract pure helpers without changing public behavior.\\n3. Rename only private functions first; preserve exported names or add aliases if needed.\\n4. Add focused tests around option normalization, Rollup cleanup behavior, and Svelte plugin resolve/load return shapes.\\n5. Re-run `crimes scan --format json` and verify these finding types disappear or shrink without introducing new high-severity findings.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":42271,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":1202,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":84}}\n",
