/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r3/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## Most likely cause: `crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts`\n\n`generateInvoice` reads the system clock **7 times** directly (`5× Date.now()`, `2× new Date()`) at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. That's the classic shape of a date-boundary flake:\n\n- Multiple clock reads inside one logical operation mean the value can **straddle a boundary** (midnight, month-end, billing-period rollover) between the first and last read. An invoice computed across that boundary sees inconsistent \"today\" values in different branches of the same function.\n- Tests can't pin a fixed moment without monkey-patching `Date`, so the test is at the mercy of whatever wall time the CI runner happens to have. A test that passes at 14:00 UTC fails at 23:59:59 UTC when one of those 7 reads lands on the next day.\n- `src/date.ts` (`crime_00005`) has 5 more direct clock reads — likely the helpers `billing.ts` is calling, so the non-determinism compounds.\n\nThe 204-line `generateInvoice` (`crime_00001`) makes this worse: with 7 clock reads spread across that body, it's very plausible different branches resolve \"now\" inconsistently.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\n1. **Inject a clock.** Add a `Clock` interface (`now(): number` or `now(): Date`) and thread it through `generateInvoice` and the helpers in `src/date.ts`. Default to a real clock in production; pass a fixed clock in tests.\n2. **Capture \"now\" once per invoice.** Inside `generateInvoice`, read the clock exactly once at the top and reuse that value — no boundary can be crossed mid-function.\n3. **Add a boundary-pinned test.** With the injected clock, write a test that pins `now` to `23:59:59.500` on a billing-period boundary and asserts the invoice's period/dates are stable. That regression test is what the current suite is missing.\n\nSecondary contributors worth noting but not load-bearing for this bug: `crime_00006` (a billing test with zero assertions — explains why this slipped through) and `crime_00016` (the `creates an invoice` test uses only weak matchers, so it likely wouldn't catch a wrong date even when it runs).",
