/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.9.3/claude/plan-01-date-string-concat.json:7:  "response": "# Migration plan: `date_string_concat` findings\n\n## Scope\n\nThe scan reports **one** `date_string_concat` finding (`crime_00026`) in this repo. The plan is therefore a single-site migration, not a sweep.\n\nNote: `crime_00026`'s line 41 also collides with `crime_00004` (Half-UTC, Half-Local) which flags the same receiver. The replacement below resolves both at once.\n\n---\n\n## Finding: `crime_00026` — `src/date.ts:41`\n\n**Evidence (verbatim):**\n> - \"`\\\"…\\\" + .getUTCFullYear()` @L41\"\n> - \"lines: 41\"\n> - \"use `toISOString()` or `Intl.DateTimeFormat` instead of `+`-concatenation\"\n\n**Suggested action (verbatim):**\n> \"Replace the concatenation with `d.toISOString()`, `Intl.DateTimeFormat(locale, opts).format(d)`, or a timezone-aware library's formatter.\"\n\n**Current code (`src/date.ts:39–42`):**\n```ts\nexport function dateLabel(): string {\n  const d = new Date();\n  return d.getUTCFullYear() + \"-\" + d.getMonth() + \"-\" + d.getDate();\n}\n```\n\n### Classification: **user-facing → `Intl.DateTimeFormat`**\n\nThe function is named `dateLabel` (a render-side concern) and is one of two display-layer helpers in this file (the other being `prettyDueDate` at L45–47). It returns a label, not an identifier or persistence key — there is no caller treating the string as a sortable/parseable ISO value. The right family is `Intl.DateTimeFormat`.\n\n`toISOString()` would also work mechanically, but it would lock the label to `YYYY-MM-DDTHH:mm:ss.sssZ` formatting, which is wrong for UI.\n\n### Proposed replacement\n\n```ts\nconst DATE_LABEL_FORMAT = new Intl.DateTimeFormat(\"en-CA\", {\n  year: \"numeric\",\n  month: \"2-digit\",\n  day: \"2-digit\",\n  timeZone: \"UTC\",\n});\n\nexport function dateLabel(): string {\n  return DATE_LABEL_FORMAT.format(new Date());\n}\n```\n\nWhy these choices:\n- **`en-CA`** produces `YYYY-MM-DD`, matching the original literal's shape.\n- **`2-digit` month/day** fixes the zero-padding bug the evidence calls out (`+ \"-\" + d.getMonth()` would render `2026-4-7` for April 7).\n- **`timeZone: \"UTC\"`** resolves `crime_00004`'s mixed-family bug — the original mixed `getUTCFullYear()` with `getMonth()`/`getDate()` (local). Pinning to UTC matches the file-level intent (most other reads are UTC) and removes the silent host-offset drift.\n- **`Intl.DateTimeFormat` is also zero-indexed-safe** — `getMonth()` returns 0–11, which is the bug the original `+ \"-\" + d.getMonth()` produces; the formatter handles month numbering correctly.\n- The formatter is **hoisted to module scope** so the locale data is constructed once, not per call.\n\n### Test\n\nAdd a Vitest case that pins a fixed `Date` and asserts the literal string `\"2026-04-07\"` (or whichever date). This proves both the zero-padding fix and the UTC pinning.\n\n---\n\n## When `toISOString()` would have been the answer instead\n\nFor completeness, the heuristic the scenario asks about:\n\n- **`toISOString()`** — when the string is consumed by code (DB column, API payload, cache key, filename, sort key, log line meant for machine parsing). Stable, sortable, timezone-explicit (`Z`). The existing `nowIso()` at `src/date.ts:13` is the correct shape already.\n- **`Intl.DateTimeFormat`** — when the string is consumed by a human (UI label, email subject, PDF cell). Locale-aware, format-flexible, but **not** parseable.\n\nNo other finding in this scan crosses into the persistence/ID bucket, so `toISOString()` is not the right call for this single migration.\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope (flagged for follow-up)\n\nThese appear on adjacent lines but are different findings — calling them out so a future pass doesn't miss them:\n\n- `crime_00027` (`src/date.ts:46`, `toLocaleDateString()` with no locale) — same \"use `Intl.DateTimeFormat`\" answer, different detector.\n- `crime_00010` (`src/date.ts:29, 33`, timezone-unsafe parse literals).\n- `crime_00014` (`src/date.ts:52`, DST-naive ms arithmetic).\n- `crime_00003` / `crime_00009` / `crime_00024` (clock injection across `src/date.ts`, `src/billing.ts`, `src/api/state.ts`).\n\nThese should be planned separately rather than bundled, since the right fix family differs (locale arg vs. zone-aware parser vs. calendar lib vs. clock injection).",
