/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/context-04-monorepo.json:7:  "response": "## Finding: `crime_00011` — Missing Agent Context (medium, conf 0.9, agent_risk 0.61)\n\nThe scan confirms the repo ships **no agent-readable instruction file**:\n\n- no `AGENTS.md` at repo root\n- no `CLAUDE.md` at repo root\n- no `.claude/skills/*/SKILL.md`\n- `package.json` declares bins (`tsup`, `tsup-node`) with no discoverable doc surface\n\n## Consequence for future agent work\n\nAn agent landing in this repo cold has to **infer** everything: which command builds (`tsup` vs `tsc`?), which tests to run, what the package layout means (`src/esbuild/`, `src/rollup.ts`, `src/api-extractor.ts` are all separate build paths inside one tool), and what's load-bearing. The same scan flags `src/plugin.ts` (fan-in 10), `src/utils.ts` (fan-in 18), and `src/index.ts` (459-line god file with a 293-line `build` function) — all places where a confident-but-wrong edit is easy without a map. Result: more wasted turns, more risk of touching the wrong layer (the boundary between `esbuild/`, `rollup.ts`, and `tsc.ts` is non-obvious from filenames alone).\n\n## Minimal `AGENTS.md` skeleton (clears the finding)\n\n```markdown\n# AGENTS.md\n\n## What this is\ntsup — a TypeScript/JavaScript bundler powered by esbuild, with Rollup\nused only for `.d.ts` generation. Single package, not a monorepo.\n\n## Commands\n- Install:  `pnpm install`\n- Build:    `pnpm build`        (runs tsup on itself)\n- Test:     `pnpm test`         (vitest, in `test/`)\n- Lint:     `pnpm lint`\n- Typecheck: `pnpm typecheck`\n\nAlways run `pnpm test` before declaring a change done.\n\n## Layout\n- `src/index.ts`         — public API entry (`build()`); orchestrates a run\n- `src/cli-main.ts`      — CLI argument parsing and dispatch\n- `src/esbuild/`         — esbuild pipeline + plugins (postcss, svelte, swc)\n- `src/rollup.ts`        — Rollup pipeline used only for `.d.ts` rollups\n- `src/api-extractor.ts` — alternative `.d.ts` path via API Extractor\n- `src/tsc.ts`           — `.d.ts` emit via `tsc`\n- `src/plugin.ts`        — internal plugin interface (high fan-in; edit carefully)\n- `src/utils.ts`         — shared helpers (high fan-in; additive changes preferred)\n- `test/`                — vitest specs; fixtures under `test/fixtures/`\n\n## Conventions\n- TypeScript strict mode; no `any` in new code.\n- Public API changes go through `src/index.ts` and need a changeset\n  (`pnpm changeset`).\n- The three `.d.ts` paths (`rollup.ts`, `api-extractor.ts`, `tsc.ts`)\n  are alternatives selected by user config — don't merge them.\n\n## Load-bearing files (read before editing)\n- `src/plugin.ts`, `src/utils.ts`, `src/index.ts`, `src/log.ts`\n  Prefer additive edits; restructuring ripples widely.\n\n## Safety\n- Don't introduce `Date.now()` / `new Date()` in domain code — inject a\n  clock. Existing instances in `api-extractor.ts`, `esbuild/index.ts`,\n  `rollup.ts`, `tsc.ts` are timing logs and should also be migrated.\n- Don't commit changes to `dist/` or `assets/cjs_shims.js`.\n```\n\nThat's ~40 lines and would flip `crime_00011` from medium to absent on the next scan. Everything in it is **discoverable from the repo** (commands from `package.json`, layout from `src/`, load-bearing files from the scan's fan-in/fan-out findings) — so the cost of writing it is low and the agent-risk reduction is immediate.",
