/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.9.3/claude/context-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## What `src/billing.ts` does\n\nIt's a 310-line billing module containing 5 top-level functions. The two named ones are:\n- `generateInvoice` (lines 50–253) — a 204-line \"god function\" mixing unrelated responsibilities\n- `calculateRefundPreview` (lines 40–44) — name suggests pure calculation, but body calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail` (side effects)\n\nThe module deals with the `\"enterprise\"` plan concept and encodes a refund rule in a comment near line 39: *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.\"* It reads the wall clock directly in many places (7× `Date.now()` / `new Date()` across lines 57–273).\n\n## Related files I'd want to read before editing\n\n- **`src/billing.test.ts`** — its only two tests are both flagged as weak (one has 0 asserts, the other uses only weak matchers). So existing tests won't catch regressions.\n- **`src/api/plan.ts`, `src/jobs/plan-sync.ts`, `src/ui/pricing.ts`** — all three duplicate the `\"enterprise\"` literal that billing uses. Any policy change here likely needs to ripple to those.\n- **`src/date.ts`** — billing's `Date.now()`/`new Date()` calls probably belong behind helpers here; this file has its own pile of temporal crimes (mixed UTC/local, unsafe parse, DST-naive math) that could leak into billing's behaviour.\n\n## Risks the scan flagged on `src/billing.ts`\n\n| Severity | Charge | Where |\n|---|---|---|\n| high | God Function (`generateInvoice`, 204 lines) | L50–253 |\n| medium | Temporal Recklessness (7× direct `Date`) | L57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 |\n| medium | String Sprinkles (`\"enterprise\"` in 4 files) | L7 + 3 sibling files |\n| medium | False Identity (`calculateRefundPreview` does I/O) | L40–44 |\n| medium | God File (310 lines, threshold 300) | whole file |\n| medium | Logic in the Alibi (refund rule lives in a comment) | L39 |\n| low | Unfinished Business (4 TODO/FIXME markers) | L183–308 |\n\nEditing risk concentrates around `generateInvoice` (size hides cross-section coupling), the refund-comment rule (easy to miss when changing refund logic), and the `\"enterprise\"` literal (any policy edit here needs to be mirrored in three siblings, or centralised first).",
