/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/review-01-oversized-raster.json:7:  "response": "# Review: `src/assets/hero-banner.png`\n\n**File size (quoted from evidence):** `byte size: 260,000 bytes (253.9 KB)`.\n\n**Verdict: request changes — do not block.**\n\nThe finding is `severity: low` (just over the 200 KB rung, well under the 500 KB / 1000 KB ladders) and `agent_risk: 0.52`. A hero banner above the fold is the wrong asset to wave through at a quarter-megabyte — it loads on every cold landing-page visit and tanks LCP — but it's also not a release-blocker against a single low-severity finding. Request the re-encode in the PR, merge once the new asset lands.\n\n## Recommended transformation\n\n**Target dimensions (intrinsic, for the source asset):**\n\n- **1600 × 900** (16:9) at 1× density, **paired with a `srcset`** that downsizes to 1280w, 960w, 640w for smaller viewports.\n- If the design renders true-full-bleed and you want crisp retina, bump the largest variant to **1920 × 1080** — anything larger is wasted bytes since most hero viewports render at ≤1440 CSS px.\n- Don't ship one giant PNG and let the browser scale it; that's how 253.9 KB happens. Use `<img srcset=\"...\" sizes=\"100vw\">` so phones don't pay for desktop pixels.\n\n**Format: AVIF, with a WebP fallback in `<picture>`.**\n\nWhy AVIF over WebP for *this* asset:\n\n1. **Hero banners are the asset where bytes matter most** — single, above-the-fold, on the critical render path. AVIF typically beats WebP by 20–40% at equivalent perceptual quality, which is the difference between ~80 KB and ~120 KB at these dimensions.\n2. **As of 2026, AVIF support is universal** across Safari 16+, Chrome, Firefox, and Edge. There's no meaningful coverage argument left for picking WebP as the primary format.\n3. **WebP belongs in the fallback `<source>`** for any ancient browser still in the long tail — cheap belt-and-suspenders, no downside.\n\nWebP would be the right call if this were a high-churn asset (faster encode, simpler tooling) or if the encoding pipeline already standardized on WebP and adding AVIF means new infra. For a one-off hero, that tradeoff doesn't apply — pay the one-time encode cost and ship AVIF.\n\n**Expected outcome:** 1600×900 AVIF at quality ~50–60 should land around **40–80 KB**, a 70–85% reduction from the current 253.9 KB.",
