/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/bugfix-04-weak-tests.json:7:  "response": "**Strengthen first: `test/index.test.ts` lines 537–548** — the `native-node-module plugin should handle *.node(.js) import properly` test.\n\nIt's the only weak-test finding that names a plugin in its title, and per `crime_00026` the evidence is:\n\n> - `test: \"native-node-module plugin should handle *.node(.js) import properly\"`\n> - `0 expect/assert calls`\n> - `lines 537-548`\n\nZero assertions on a test whose entire purpose is to protect plugin behaviour explains exactly how an esbuild plugin regression passes CI: the test only proves the build didn't throw. Every other weak-signal finding either targets dts/tsconfig/shims/graphql flows (`crime_00018`–`crime_00025`, `crime_00027`–`crime_00029`) or uses weak matchers on non-plugin behaviour (`crime_00058`–`crime_00071`) — none of those guard the esbuild plugin path.\n\n**Assertion to add:** after the build runs, read the emitted bundle and assert it contains the rewritten `require(...)` (or `createRequire`) call for the `*.node` / `*.node.js` import, e.g. `expect(output).toMatch(/require\\(['\"].+\\.node['\"]\\)/)` and `expect(output).not.toContain('import ')` for the native module specifier. That pins the observable contract — \"the plugin actually rewrote the native-module import\" — which is precisely what the regression would have broken while the current setup-only test stayed green.",
