/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/refactor-04-monorepo.json:7:  "response": "# Refactor plan — three files, three finding types\n\nI'll work straight from the JSON in the prompt rather than re-scanning. The \"petty\" cluster across `src/index.ts`, `src/rollup.ts`, and `src/esbuild/svelte.ts` breaks down into three finding types. Each section names the offenders, explains the agent trap, and proposes a concrete fix.\n\n---\n\n## 1. False Identity (`name_behavior_mismatch`)\n\n| Finding | Symbol | Side-effect evidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| crime_00032 | `src/index.ts:build` (167–459) | `createLogger`, `removeFiles`, 4 side-effect signals |\n| crime_00054 | `src/index.ts:buildAll` (291–365) | `removeFiles`, 3 side-effect signals |\n| crime_00049 | `src/rollup.ts:getRollupConfig` (38–159) | `setSilent`, `removeFiles`, 4 side-effect signals |\n| crime_00072 | `src/rollup.ts:buildStart` (77–81) | `removeFiles`, 2 side-effect signals |\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today.** All four names imply pure reads (`build` reads like a noun-builder/factory, `getRollupConfig` reads like a getter, `buildStart` reads like a lifecycle no-op). An agent extending this code is likely to:\n\n- Memoize `getRollupConfig` to avoid \"recomputing config\" — silently dropping the `clean`/`setSilent` calls on cache hits.\n- Call `build()` twice in a watcher loop (e.g. \"compute first, run later\") — deleting files twice.\n- Wrap `buildStart` in a debounce — turning a clean-before-build into an intermittent clean.\n\n**Proposal.**\n\n- **`build` → `runBuild`.** Extract a pure `resolveBuildPlan(options): BuildPlan` step; have `runBuild` accept that plan and own the logger/`removeFiles` side effects. This also cuts the 293-line God Function (crime_00003) into separable units.\n- **`buildAll` → `runAllBuilds`.** Hoist the `removeFiles` call to the caller (or guard it behind a one-shot flag) so the per-build function is genuinely side-effect-free.\n- **`getRollupConfig` → split.** Rename to `buildRollupConfig` (or `prepareRollupBuild`) and extract two helpers: `applyLogLevel(opts)` and `cleanOutDirs(opts)`. The function is currently a getter that destroys filesystem state — that's the heart of the agent risk.\n- **`buildStart`.** The name is fixed by Rollup's plugin contract, so don't rename. Instead, gate the `removeFiles` call behind `if (options.clean)` and add a one-line comment naming the side effect — that's the minimum disclosure.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Option Bag Junk Drawer (`option_bag_junk_drawer`)\n\n| Finding | Symbol | Property reads |\n|---|---|---|\n| crime_00053 | `src/rollup.ts:getRollupConfig` | 10: `cjsInterop, clean, dts, entry, external, format, outDir, outExtension, …` |\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today.** `getRollupConfig(options)` accepts the full `NormalizedOptions` and pulls 10 fields out of it implicitly. An agent that:\n\n- Adds a new option (`outDirs` plural, `dtsEntry` separate) won't know whether to wire it here — the function reads the bag opaquely.\n- Removes a field they grep-confirmed is \"only read in `index.ts`\" can silently break this codepath because the property access is hidden inside method bodies.\n- Tries to reuse `getRollupConfig` from a test by passing a `{}` literal — TypeScript accepts it (the param is the wide `NormalizedOptions`), runtime fails on the first missing field.\n\n**Proposal.** Replace `options: NormalizedOptions` with an explicit, narrower shape:\n\n```ts\ntype RollupConfigInputs = Pick<\n  NormalizedOptions,\n  'cjsInterop' | 'clean' | 'dts' | 'entry' | 'external'\n  | 'format' | 'outDir' | 'outExtension' | 'silent' | /* …the remaining 1 */\n>;\n```\n\nEven better: destructure at the call site so each helper takes only what it needs. That converts the agent's question from \"does this function use field X?\" to a type error.\n\nThe same pattern applies to crime_00050 (`runEsbuild` reads 38 distinct properties) and crime_00056/57 (`main` reads 8) — the user scoped the question to the three named files, but the same `Pick<>`/destructure recipe lifts straight over.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Return Shape Roulette (`return_shape_roulette`)\n\n| Finding | Symbol | Shapes | Example divergence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00051 | `src/esbuild/svelte.ts:sveltePlugin` (9–124) | 6, 0% overlap | `{ args, namespace, path }` vs `{ location, text }` |\n| crime_00052 | `src/esbuild/svelte.ts:setup` (17–122) | 6, 0% overlap | same — `setup` is the inner callback of `sveltePlugin` |\n| crime_00055 | `src/esbuild/svelte.ts:<anonymous>` (31–121) | 5, 0% overlap | `{ location, text }` vs `{ code }` |\n\n**What an agent gets wrong today.** Without an annotated return type, TS infers the union `{args,namespace,path} | {location,text} | {code} | …`. The shapes are esbuild plugin callbacks (`onResolve` → `OnResolveResult`, `onLoad` → `OnLoadResult`, errors → `PartialMessage`, transform → `{ code }`), but the file doesn't *say* that. An agent who:\n\n- Adds an error path returning `{ message: 'svelte preprocess failed' }` gets no TS error — esbuild silently ignores the unknown shape and the diagnostic disappears.\n- Refactors one branch into a helper and lifts the inferred return type as the helper's signature — now every caller pays for the union and the next agent assumes all branches return all fields.\n- Tries to add a `pluginData` field to the resolve result by spreading it onto the error-path return.\n\n**Proposal.** Annotate each callback explicitly with esbuild's exported types:\n\n```ts\nimport type {\n  OnResolveResult, OnLoadResult, PartialMessage,\n} from 'esbuild';\n\nbuild.onResolve({ filter }, async (args): Promise<OnResolveResult | undefined> => { … });\nbuild.onLoad({ filter }, async (args): Promise<OnLoadResult> => { … });\n```\n\nThat single change converts all three findings on this file: future divergent shapes fail at the type checker instead of at runtime, and an agent reading the file sees the contract without having to infer it from six return statements.\n\n---\n\n## Order of operations\n\n1. **Group 3 first (svelte.ts annotations).** Pure type additions, zero behavior change, removes three findings.\n2. **Group 1 renames + side-effect extraction.** Touches more files but each rename is mechanical; the `getRollupConfig` split also chips at the God Function in crime_00008.\n3. **Group 2 (`RollupConfigInputs`).** Do last — narrowing the type may surface bugs in the call sites that the prior two steps haven't already touched.\n\nNone of these are load-bearing in the high_fan_in_fan_out sense for the three target files (`rollup.ts` fan-in 0, `svelte.ts` not in the connectivity tier, `index.ts` is fan-in 4 but the renames are internal). Safe to do without an importer survey.",
