/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.9.3/claude/refactor-01-svg-embedded-raster.json:7:  "response": "## Finding (crime_00001 — `svg_with_embedded_raster`, high severity)\n\nFrom the evidence:\n- **2 embedded base64 rasters** inside `src/assets/partner-logo.svg`\n- **MIME types: `image/jpeg` and `image/png`**\n- SVG byte size 592 bytes (mostly base64 overhead, not vector geometry)\n\n## Remediation plan\n\n**1. Treat the two embedded rasters differently based on their MIME type.**\n\n- **The `image/png` payload** — almost certainly a flat graphic element (logomark, badge, wordmark, gradient swatch). PNG is what design tools dump when they flatten a vector layer they couldn't export cleanly. Re-author this region as **native SVG paths** (`<path>`, `<polygon>`, `<circle>`, with `<linearGradient>` / `<radialGradient>` for any color ramps). Re-export from the source file (Figma / Illustrator / Sketch) with \"flatten raster\" turned **off** and \"outline strokes\" on.\n- **The `image/jpeg` payload** — JPEG is a photographic codec; no vector tool emits JPEG unless the source layer was a photo (partner headshot, product shot, textured background). That genuinely cannot be re-authored as paths without losing the content. **Split it out to a standalone raster asset**, e.g. `src/assets/partner-logo-photo.webp` (or `.jpg` if WebP isn't acceptable), sized to its rendered dimensions.\n\n**2. After the refactor, `partner-logo.svg` should contain only vector geometry.** Two acceptable shapes for the final file:\n\n- **Preferred — pure vector, no external references.** The JPEG content is removed from the logo entirely (a logo with a photo inside is usually a design mistake), and the SVG ships `<path>` / `<g>` elements only. The SVG no longer references any other file.\n- **If the photo must stay**, the SVG keeps an `<image href=\"/assets/partner-logo-photo.webp\" .../>` element pointing at the split-out asset by URL — *not* a `data:` URI. After refactor the SVG would reference exactly one file: `src/assets/partner-logo-photo.webp`.\n\n**3. Verify.** Re-run `crimes scan --format json` and confirm `svg_with_embedded_raster` no longer fires. Expected byte size drops from 592 b (mostly base64) to whatever the vector path data is — typically smaller than the original even with the split-out raster counted separately, because the base64 overhead is gone and the photo is delivered in a format actually designed for photos.\n\nThe file at `src/assets/partner-logo.svg` is preserved throughout — only its contents change.",
