/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/refactor-06-stress-duplication.json:7:  "response": "## Duplication confirmed\n\n`crimes scan` flags one near-duplicate cluster (`crime_00002`) covering three files with the same body and renamed identifiers only:\n\n- `src/sanitize-a.ts:10-36` — `sanitizeUserInput(raw)`\n- `src/sanitize-b.ts:9-35` — `sanitizeText(input)`\n- `src/sanitize-c.ts:9-35` — `cleanMessage(value)`\n\nI read all three: the bodies are byte-for-byte identical modulo the variable name (`working` / `cleaned` / `normalised`) and the parameter name. Same trim, same `[ -]` strip, same `\\s+` collapse, same 1000-char cap, same `<`/`>` reject, same `\\\\x` reject, same `[!?]{3,}` punctuation count, same upper-case ratio downcase. No semantic divergence to preserve.\n\nThe `assertAdmin{A,B,C}` guards at the top of each file are **not** identical — they're the duplicated-role-check finding (`crime_00003`), and they actually diverge:\n\n- A: `role === \"admin\"`\n- B: `role === \"admin\" || role === \"owner\"`\n- C: `role !== \"admin\"` (negated)\n\nThose need a separate conversation — collapsing them blindly would change behaviour. Leaving them out of this refactor.\n\n## Proposed consolidation\n\n**New module:** `src/sanitize.ts` (single source of truth).\n\n**Public API:**\n\n```ts\nexport function sanitize(value: unknown): string;\n```\n\nRationale:\n\n- One name. The three existing names (`sanitizeUserInput` / `sanitizeText` / `cleanMessage`) are just synonyms — pick the shortest accurate one.\n- `unknown` parameter type covers all three callers without breaking them: each currently accepts `string` but immediately guards `null`/`undefined` and coerces with `String(value)`. `unknown` makes that explicit at the boundary and lets callers stop pre-checking.\n- Pure, synchronous, no clock or env reads — keep it that way so it stays trivially testable.\n- Magic numbers (`1000` length cap, `5` punctuation threshold, `0.9` upper-case ratio, `30` minimum length for downcase) stay inlined. They're not parameters today; promoting them to options would be scope creep. If a caller ever needs different limits, add an optional `options` arg then.\n\n## Files that change\n\n| File | Change |\n|---|---|\n| `src/sanitize.ts` | **New.** Holds the single `sanitize` implementation. |\n| `src/sanitize-a.ts` | Delete `sanitizeUserInput`. Keep `assertAdminA` (separate concern). If `sanitizeUserInput` has external callers, re-export: `export { sanitize as sanitizeUserInput } from \"./sanitize\"` — or, preferably, update call sites and delete. |\n| `src/sanitize-b.ts` | Same treatment: delete `sanitizeText`, keep `assertAdminB`. |\n| `src/sanitize-c.ts` | Same treatment: delete `cleanMessage`, keep `assertAdminC`. |\n| Call sites | Anywhere that imports `sanitizeUserInput` / `sanitizeText` / `cleanMessage` switches to `import { sanitize } from \"./sanitize\"`. (Grep before deleting to confirm the blast radius.) |\n\nIf the three `assertAdmin*` guards turn out to be unintentional drift rather than three real policies, fold them into a single `isAdmin(role)` in a follow-up — but verify the semantics with whoever owns each call site first; `crime_00003` flagged this exact risk.\n\nOut of scope here: the `Date.now()` calls in `telemetry-a.ts` / `telemetry-b.ts` (`crime_00004`/`00005`) and the duplicated `recordSanitiseEvent` (`crime_00001`). Those are a separate refactor with their own API question (inject a clock).",
