/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.9.3/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## Most likely cause\n\n**crime_00004 (Half-UTC, Half-Local) combined with crime_00010 (Timezone Roulette) in `src/date.ts`.**\n\nThe smoking gun is the variable `d` at `src/date.ts:9,41` — it reads `getUTCFullYear()` on one line and `getMonth()` (local) on another. The two families disagree by the host's UTC offset, so any computation that crosses midnight UTC will produce a different year/month than the test expects. That's exactly the shape of a \"date-boundary\" flake: passes when the dev machine is in UTC or close to it, fails on CI runners in a different zone (or vice versa).\n\nCompounding it:\n- **crime_00010**: `new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")` and `new Date(\"2026-12-20\")` have no zone marker. The first is parsed in *local* time per ECMAScript; the second is parsed as *UTC*. Round-tripping these through a function that also mixes UTC/local methods will silently shift the date by up to a day at the boundary.\n- **crime_00014**: `+ 86400000` for \"one day\" drifts an hour on DST-transition days, which can push a result across midnight.\n- **crime_00009 + crime_00003**: `billing.ts` calls `Date.now()`/`new Date()` directly 7 times and depends on `date.ts`, so the test cannot pin wall-time without monkey-patching. A flaky boundary becomes invisible until the wall clock happens to land near it.\n\n## Proposed fix (in order)\n\n1. **`src/date.ts:9,41` — pick one family per receiver.** Convert the mixed reads on `d` to all-UTC (recommended for storage/billing math). This is the single highest-leverage change and should make the failing test deterministic.\n2. **`src/date.ts:29,33` — append `Z` to the literals** (`\"2026-12-25T07:00:00Z\"`, `\"2026-12-20T00:00:00Z\"`) or parse through Luxon/Temporal so the zone is explicit, not inherited.\n3. **`src/date.ts:52` — replace `+ 86400000` with a calendar-aware `addDays`** (Luxon/Temporal/date-fns-tz). This kills the DST drift class entirely.\n4. **`src/billing.ts` — inject a clock.** Pass `now()` into `generateInvoice` (and friends) instead of calling `Date.now()` inline. Then write a regression test that pins `now()` to the offending boundary moment so this can't silently recur.\n\nStep 1 alone is the most likely fix for the failing test; steps 2–4 close the surrounding hazard so the bug doesn't move next door.",
